[{"id":"VR095561","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR095450.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Based on the data in the graph, which of the following proposed solutions would have the greatest effect on reducing global water withdrawals?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR095561_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a bar graph with 5 bars of data titled “Water Withdrawal Over Time.” The vertical axis is labeled Water Withdrawal, in cubic kilometers per year, and the numbers 0 through 4,500, in increments of 500, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled Year and the following five years are shown, 1970, 1980, 1990, 2000, and 2010. Each bar is composed of three categories: Agricultural, Industrial, and Municipal. The data represented by the bars are as follows. Note that all values are approximate. Bar 1, year 1970 has a total of 2,500 cubic kilometers per year with the following breakdown. Agricultural, 1,850 cubic kilometers per year; Industrial, 500 cubic kilometers per year; Municipal, 150 cubic kilometers per year. Bar 2, year 1980 has a total of 3,100 cubic kilometers per year with the following breakdown. Agricultural, 2,200 cubic kilometers per year; Industrial, 700 cubic kilometers per year; Municipal, 200 cubic kilometers per year. Bar 3, year 1990 has a total of 3,400 cubic kilometers per year with the following breakdown. Agricultural, 2,400 cubic kilometers per year; Industrial, 700 cubic kilometers per year; Municipal, 300 cubic kilometers per year. Bar 4, year 2000 has a total of 3,700 cubic kilometers per year with the following breakdown. Agricultural, 2,600 cubic kilometers per year; Industrial, 750 cubic kilometers per year; Municipal, 350 cubic kilometers per year. Bar 5, year 2010 has a total of 3,900 cubic kilometers per year with the following breakdown. Agricultural, 2,700 cubic kilometers per year; Industrial, 800 cubic kilometers per year; Municipal, 400 cubic kilometers per year.\" height=\"464\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR095450.g04.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">A coordinated public information campaign in rural areas about household water conservation.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Government grants to assist farmers with the up-front installation costs of drip irrigation systems.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Tax incentives for industries that reuse at least 10% of the water they withdraw for industrial processes.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">An increase in the use of agricultural water to increase crop production in arid areas.</p>"],"answer":1}]